"Yes, sir. They must be on their way now; we gave them time to get provisions at the mess hall." At exactly 5:00 A.M., Company Exodus was assembled at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We are deploying towards FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We must support the ongoing siege and the planned attack on Ianlos to quell the uprising. From there, we will have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Gather your units and board."
The company dispersed, each one joining their unit, and the sergeants got them into the tanks. Cohren climbed into one of the armored vehicles, at the front of the column, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he knew very little about them. Sitting on the side, his legs dangling, he adjusted his pack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat mic.
"Hey Cohren, does Harris still have Snowball?" asked Nemic as they settled in.
"The chicken he stole, you mean?" Cohren remembered the morning when they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure of it."
Cohren threw a glance at one of the tanks and saw Harris with his unit. From the rear of his backpack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken waving its head to observe the surroundings.
"Yeah, he always does," replied Cohren as the turret of the tank opened with a clatter to let through its commander.
"All the tanks were on their way," declared the commander calmly but clearly through his helmet. The engines of a platoon of tanks and Strykers roared as they began to advance. The Kronos on which Cohren was riding had a jolt when its brakes were released and it started moving into formation. The tanks deployed in a V formation to cross the plains of Itania. The winter storms had frozen the marshes and forests, but the mud was still there.
About an hour later, one of the new recruits, known to Cohren as Orson, spoke up. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the beginning of the war, haven't you?"
"Yeah, Operation Inferno Storm," replied Cohren. "We thought we'd wrap it up in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimate is a mild term," said Nemic as he joined the conversation. "They had more weapons and men than we anticipated. They managed to bring down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Hell, we should be able to see them from where we are."
"Well, I'll hold my ground for the Federation," said Orson, slightly provocative. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You say that now, but from experience, I know that new recruits like you start hiding the moment you hear gunfire," declared Craith.
"I think we'll soon find out," said Corhen, laughing. Orson did not follow up on the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We're detecting thermal signatures about 300 meters, 20 degrees right."
Cohren climbed to the top of the chariot and put on his optical glasses. Activating thermal vision, he could see thermal signatures in the distance.
"Yep, I can see them," Cohren replied through his throat mic.
"Enemies?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Can't tell for sure," declared Cohren. He activated his mic and said: "Exodus Company, don't fire until fired upon, let's get them out."
As they approached, the small thermal signatures transitioned from blurry spots to more distinct shapes. As they got closer, one of them ran towards something, picked it up, and then rushed back to the small ridge where they were. The figures took their firing positions.
"We have contact," Shaw shouted into the radio as tracer rounds were fired from the crest. Bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks while soldiers jumped from their vehicles to take cover behind them. A tank-killing missile whistled overhead and hit the ground behind the formation, exploding and sending debris onto one of the vehicles. Another missile struck the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew emerged and dived for cover as the ammunition burned.
"Iron 1-2 and -, 25 degrees right, 275 meters. Fire," shouted the tank platoon commander into the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells hurtling towards the crest and exploding, throwing dirt and rocks into the air.
"Send the Sentis," Knoxx yelled, observing the crest through his binoculars. The back of one of the Cerberus opened up, and an unarmed soldier wearing a special helmet emerged. He barked orders into a square microphone, and two Sentinels, or as they were officially named, Sentinelas, dashed out. Their slender metal limbs swung forward as they sprinted, but their weapons were attached to their backs.
"Kill them or capture them?" Craith asked as they watched.
"It appears we're capturing them," Cohren said as the two Sentinels disappeared in a cloud of ash and smoke. Screams and gunfire echoed from the crest but quickly ceased. A moment later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots dragged on the ground. Once safely with the platoon, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he collapsed in the mud and snow.
Shaw walked towards the individual, who was beginning to get up. He turned towards one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, chief," replied the Sentinel. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned towards Cohren and Craith, who were standing beside him. "Both of you, would you be so kind as to rid us of this man?"
